# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bandung
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] For the first time, the Summer Asian Games were co-hosted by two regions; the Indonesian capital of Jakarta (which was hosting the Games for the first time since 1962), and Palembang, the capital of South Sumatra province.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Events were held in and around the two cities, including venues in Bandung and the provinces of West Java and Banten.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The opening and closing ceremonies of the Games were held at Gelora Bung Karno Stadium in Jakarta.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Games were originally awarded to Hanoi, Vietnam, but withdrew in 2014 due to budgetary concerns and other factors.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Several non-Olympic events were trimmed from the event programme, but several new disciplines being introduced at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo (including 3-on-3 basketball) were added.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Esports and canoe polo were also contested as demonstration sports.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] China led the medal tally for the tenth consecutive time.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] North and South Korea fielded a unified team during the opening ceremony and selected events, and also won their first-ever gold medal as a unified team at a multi-sport event.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] 6 world, 18 Asian and 86 Asian Games records were broken during the Games, while Japanese swimmer Rikako Ikee was announced as the most valuable player.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The OCA originally planned to hold these Games in 2019 rather than 2018, so that Asian Games would be held exactly a year before the 2020 Summer Olympics instead of the same year as the 2018 Winter Olympics.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] After they were awarded to Indonesia, the OCA backtracked on these plans and kept the Games in 2018, so that they would not interfere with the 2019 Indonesian general election.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Hanoi, Vietnam was originally selected to be the host after they won the bid against two other candidates, Surabaya and Dubai.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] They were awarded the winning bid on 8 November 2012, with 29 votes against Surabaya's 14 votes.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Dubai pulled out at the last minute, instead announcing their intention to focus on future bids.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The UAE's National Olympic Committee's vice-president denied any pullout and claimed that Dubai "did not apply for hosting 2019 Asian Games" and had "only considered" doing so.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] However, in March 2014, there were some concerns about Vietnam's ability to host.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] These included concerns over whether the anticipated budget of US$150 million was realistic.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] There were claims that the government would eventually spend over US$300 million.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] In addition, critics were concerned that several stadiums built in conjunction with the 2003 Southeast Asian Games had not been utilized since.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Former chairman of the Vietnam Olympic Committee Ha Quang Du also claimed that hosting the Asian Games would not boost tourism in Vietnam.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 17 April 2014, Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyễn Tấn Dũng officially announced Hanoi's withdrawal from hosting, citing unpreparedness and economic recession as the main reasons for the withdrawal, saying "they have left the country unable to afford the construction of facilities and venues".
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Many Vietnamese people supported the decision to withdraw.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] No penalty was imposed for the withdrawal.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] After Hanoi's withdrawal, the OCA said that Indonesia, China, and the United Arab Emirates were major candidates under consideration to host.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Indonesia was widely regarded as a favourite, since Surabaya was the runner-up of the previous bid, and willing to do so if selected.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Philippines and India expressed their interest about hosting the Games, but India failed to submit a late bid because it was unable to get an audience with Prime Minister Narendra Modi after being given an extended deadline by the OCA.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 5 May 2014, the OCA visited several Indonesian cities, including Jakarta, Surabaya, Bandung, and Palembang.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] At this time Surabaya decided to drop their bid to host the Games and instead focus on hosting the already scheduled 2021 Asian Youth Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 25 July 2014, during a meeting in Kuwait City, the OCA appointed Jakarta as the host of the Games with Palembang as the supporting host.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] As the capital and the third biggest city on southern hemisphere, Jakarta was chosen because of its well-equipped sports facilities, adequate transportation networks, and other facilities such as hotels and lodging for guests.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 20 September 2014, Indonesia signed the host city contract, and was ceremonially appointed host during the closing ceremony of the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] An organising committee was formed soon after the appointment.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] By 2015, the central government had allocated a budget of IDR 3 trillion (US$224 million) to prepare for the Games, with regional administrations also expected to supply some part of the funding.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] By July 2018, the budget allocation for the Games had been reported to be IDR 6.6 trillion (US$450 million) including IDR 869 billion (US$59 million) from sponsorships.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The total cost of arranging the Games is estimated about US$3.2 billion, of which $2.4 billion being spent on infrastructure development associated with the games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Phase 2 volunteering programme of Jakarta-Palembang 2018 Asian Games began on 18 December 2017 with target of 13,000 volunteers being set.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The volunteers wore clothing which included jacket, polo shirts and trousers which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre at the Sports and Recreation Arena in East Jakarta.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Volunteers also wore accreditation card which gain them access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 10 May 2018, 100 days before their opening, the Asian Games torch was unveiled.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The design was inspired by the golok and skin — traditional weapons originating from Jakarta and Palembang.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The torch relay began at the Major Dhyan Chand National Stadium in New Delhi, host of the 1st Asian Games, on 15 July 2018.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The flame was generated from a parabolic mirror directed at the sun.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 18 July 2018, a ceremony took place in Brahma field by the 9th century Hindu temple of Prambanan near Yogyakarta, where the torch's flame from India were fused together with an Indonesian natural eternal flame taken from Mrapen, Central Java.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Subsequently, the Torch Relay Concert were performed marking the start of torch relay throughout the country.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The relay travelled through 54 cities in 18 provinces in Indonesia, including host cities.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The relay covered a total distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi).
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The relay finished on 17 August, the 73rd anniversary of the Proclamation of Indonesian Independence, at the National Monument in Jakarta before being carried into the opening ceremony at Gelora Bung Karno Stadium the next day.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The initial emblem for the 2018 Asian Games was first unveiled on 9 September 2015, in celebration of the country's National Sports Day.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 27 December 2015, the Games' mascot, Drawa, was unveiled by vice president Jusuf Kalla.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Both the emblem and mascot were a stylized rendition of the *cenderawasih*, a rare species of bird in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The designs were widely criticised for their outdated appearance, and Drawa in particular was criticised for having little connection to Indonesian culture and history (with some Indonesians joking that the mascot looked more like a chicken than a *cenderawasih*).
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 7 January 2016, Kalla announced that the original emblem and mascot had been withdrawn based on feedback, and that an open call for new designs would be held in partnership with the Creative Economy Agency.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Out of 60 submissions, the new emblem — entitled "Energy of Asia" — was unveiled on 28 July 2016.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The new emblem was modelled upon the Gelora Bung Karno Stadium, and was intended to symbolise unity among Asian countries.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Three new mascots were also unveiled: Bhin Bhin, a greater bird-of-paradise; Atung, a Bawean deer; and Kaka, a Javan rhinoceros.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] They represent the Eastern, Central, and Western regions of Indonesia, as well as strategy, speed and strength.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The mascots' outfits reflect traditional textiles; Bhin Bhin wears a vest with Asmat pattern details, Atung wears a *sarong* with *batik tumpal* patterns, and Kaka wears a Palembang *songket* with floral patterns.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Their names were derived from the national motto of Indonesia, *Bhinneka Tunggal Ika* (*Unity in Diversity*).
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The medal designs were unveiled in July 2018, featuring batik designs reflecting the unity and diversity of Indonesian and Asian culture.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On 18 August 2017, simultaneous events were held at Jakarta's National Monument and Palembang's Kuto Besak Fort to mark the one-year milestone before the Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The event in Jakarta was attended by president Joko Widodo, and featured performances by Taeyeon and Hyoyeon of K-pop group Girls' Generation.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Countdown clocks were unveiled at the Selamat Datang Monument and in front of Gelora Sriwijaya Stadium.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Several fun run events were held in Asian countries to promote the Games, beginning with Lahore, Pakistan in December 2017.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The games' merchandises and licensing products, which included mascot stuffed toys and other items, were sold in stores across Jakarta (including the Super Store at the Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex) from the end of 2017 to the end of September 2018.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The official theme song of the Games, "Meraih Bintang" ("Reach for the Stars"), was performed by Via Vallen.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The song was included in a larger official album for the Games, released on 13 July 2018 and featuring various Indonesian musicians.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] As part of an effort to appeal younger spectators, the Indonesian-Japanese idol group JKT48 was signed to perform at some of the Games' venues, such as jet ski, softball, and volleyball.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] They performed in select events between 19 August and 1 September in a group consisted of eight members from each of its teams.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] As part of creating a memorable and collectible item, the Indonesian postal service Pos Indonesia issued a philatelic collectible items of the 2018 Asian Games series.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] These items were issued on 18 January 2018 and 18 August 2018.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Games used a mix of new and existing venues in Jakarta and South Sumatra (with organizers aiming to reuse existing facilities and infrastructure, such as those built for the 2011 Southeast Asian Games, to help control costs), as well as Jakarta's neighbouring provinces of Banten, and West Java.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Venues were divided into four clusters, with three in Jakarta and its surrounding areas and one in Palembang.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex in Jakarta hosted 13 events.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The 56-year-old Main Stadium was refurbished for the Games, replacing its existing bleachers and seating with an all-seater design (reducing its capacity to 77,193), and adding new sound systems and LED lighting among other enhancements.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Jakarta International Velodrome at Rawamangun in East Jakarta was rebuilt, at a cost of US$40 million for cycling, badminton, futsal, basketball, and wrestling.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The Jakarta International Equestrian Park at Pulomas underwent a US$30.8 million renovation, with a capacity of 1,000, 100 stables, lodging for athletes, and other amenities.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Jakabaring Sport City was used as an event site.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] While there were preliminary plans to increase the size of Gelora Sriwijaya Stadium from 36,000 to 60,000 seats, they were shelved.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The site still underwent some renovations, including also being converted from bleachers to an all-seater.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A new 40-lane bowling alley was constructed on the complex, as well as eight additional tennis courts.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The length of the canoeing and rowing venue in Jakabaring Lake was extended to 2,300 meters, while new rowing facilities and a tribune were built on the lake shore.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Other existing venues which was used for Games were also renovated, including Ranau Sports Hall as sepak takraw venue.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A 10-hectare athletes' village was constructed in Jakarta's Kemayoran district, with 7,424 apartments in 10 towers, and a total capacity of 22,272.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A second athletes' village was built at Jakabaring Sports City at Palembang, which housed 3,000 athletes and officials.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] As part of the Games preparation, the construction of the Jakarta MRT and Jakarta LRT was accelerated, though neither were ready for general commercial operation at the time of the opening ceremonies.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A line of Jakarta LRT connected the Velodrome at Rawamangun in East Jakarta to the Kelapa Gading district of North Jakarta, connecting the Velodrome with the Equestrian Park slightly to the north.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] City bus operator Transjakarta added 416 buses to serve the officials, and also provide free rides on selected days during the Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Palembang upgraded their transportation facilities ahead for the Games by building 25 kilometres of the Palembang Light Rail Transit from Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport to Jakabaring Sports City which opened for public use in July 2018.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport is expanding its existing arrival and departure terminals to increase its capacity and also connecting the airport with the light rail transit (LRT) terminal by building a skybridge.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Other transportation facilities such as toll roads, flyovers, and bridges will be also built in and around the city.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The opening ceremony started at 19:00 Western Indonesian Time (UTC+7) on Saturday, 18 August 2018.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Wishnutama, then-CEO of Indonesian TV network NET. was the creative director for the ceremony.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The ceremony stage showcased a towering 26 meter-high mountain with a waterfall as its background, accompanied by Indonesian plants and flowers.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] North and South Korea delegates marched together under one unified flag of Korea, which marked the first time both countries did so in the Asian Games after 12 years.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The games was officially opened by the President of Indonesia, Joko Widodo.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] These changes reduced the total number of events to 431.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The final programme was unveiled in September 2017, increasing it to 462 events in 40 sports (61 disciplines) as the second-largest programme in Asian Games history.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Additional disciplines being introduced at the 2020 Summer Olympics were also added, including 3x3 basketball and BMX freestyle.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] For the first time in Asian Games history, esports and canoe polo were contested as demonstration sports in the Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Six video game titles, most notably Pro Evolution Soccer 2018, were featured in the esports events.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] All 45 members of the Olympic Council of Asia participated in the games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] North Korea and South Korea competed as a unified team in some events under the name "Korea" (COR), and marched together under the Korean Unification Flag during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] With a gold medal in the Women's 500 metre dragon boat competition, a unified team won their first-ever gold medal in a multi-sport event.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Originally set to compete as Independent Asian Athletes, the Kuwaitis were allowed to compete under their own flags just two days before the opening ceremony.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Below is a list of all the participating NOCs.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The number of competitors per delegation is indicated in brackets.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The closing ceremony started at 19:00 Western Indonesia Time (UTC+7) on Sunday, 2 September 2018 and ended at 21:25.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] In addition to local artists and a Chinese segment, the South Korean boybands Super Junior and iKon, and Indian singer Sidharth Slathia performed in the ceremony.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Mayor of Hangzhou Xu Liyi received the Games flag for the 2022 Games from Jakarta Governor Anies Baswedan and South Sumatra Governor Alex Noerdin.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] China led the medal table for the tenth consecutive time.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Korea claimed their first gold medal at the Games in the canoeing women's traditional boat race 500 m event.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A total of 37 NOCs won at least one medal, 29 NOCs won at least one gold medal and 9 NOCs failed to win any medal at the Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] International Games Broadcast Services (IGBS), a joint venture between Host Broadcast Services (HBS) and IMG Media was appointed by the organiser in July 2017 to serve as the host broadcaster for these Games.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Involving 37 live production units, it distributed 2,400 hours of the Games content to its international rights holders.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in Jakarta Convention Center, with a smaller one constructed at the Palembang cluster.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] On top of that, work in both host cities was delayed throughout 2015 because government funding was not immediately available.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Various concerns from traffic congestion problems, series of terror attacks, which local police claimed is a pre-Asian Games crackdown on terror suspects and petty street criminals, and already-provoked Indonesian fans at the venue.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Jakarta struggled with air pollution and river pollution problems.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] River pollution revealed where authorities covered a foul-smelling river near the athletes' village with black nylon mesh over fears it will be an eyesore at the showpiece event.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] Governor of Jakarta at that time, and the Indonesian Environment and Forestry Ministry quickly relieved the issues by various solutions.
[src:bandung/2018-asian-games] A doping case from a Turkmen wrestler was recorded, which jeopardize the sport's existence for future Games.
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] Elevation or altitude is generally expressed as "metres above mean sea level" in the metric system, or "feet above mean sea level" in United States customary and imperial units.
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] For elevations or altitudes, often just the abbreviation MSL is used, e.g., Mount Everest (8849 m MSL), or the reference to sea level is omitted completely, e.g., Mount Everest (8849 m).
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] Altimetry is the measurement of altitude or elevation above sea level.
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] Accurate measurement of historical mean sea levels is complex.
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] Land mass subsidence (as occurs naturally in some regions) can give the appearance of rising sea levels.
[src:bandung/above-sea-level] Conversely, markings on land masses that are uplifted (due to geological processes) can suggest a relative lowering of mean sea level.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A **village** is a human settlement or a residential community, larger than a hamlet but smaller than a town; some geographers describe villages as having between 500 and 2,500 inhabitants.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Although villages are often located in rural areas, the term urban village is also applied to certain urban neighborhoods.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages are normally permanent, with fixed dwellings, however, transient villages also exist.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Further, the dwellings of a village are fairly close to one another, not scattered broadly over the landscape, as a dispersed settlement.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the past, villages were a usual form of community for societies that practiced subsistence agriculture and also for some non-agricultural societies.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Great Britain, a hamlet earned the right to be called a village when it built a church.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In many cultures, towns and cities were few, with only a small proportion of the population living in them.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The Industrial Revolution attracted people in larger numbers to work in mills and factories; the concentration of people caused many villages to grow into towns and cities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This also enabled specialization of labor and crafts and the development of many trades.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The trend of urbanization continues but not always in connection with industrialization.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Historically, homes were situated together for sociability and defence, and land surrounding the living quarters was farmed.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Traditional fishing villages were based on artisan fishing and located adjacent to fishing grounds.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In toponomastic terminology, the names of individual villages are called *Comonyms* (from Ancient Greek κώμη / village and ὄνυμα / name, [cf. ὄνομα]).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] From Middle English *village*, from Old French *village*, from Latin *villāticus*, ultimately from Latin *villa* (English *villa*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Afghanistan, the village, or *deh* (Dari/Pashto: ده) is a mid-size settlement type in Afghan society, trumping the United States hamlet or *qala* (Dari: قلعه, Pashto: کلي), though smaller than the town, or *shār* (Dari: شهر, Pashto: ښار).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In contrast to the *qala*, the *deh* is generally a bigger settlement which includes a commercial area, while the yet larger *shār* includes governmental buildings and services such as schools of higher education, basic health care, police stations etc.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] "The soul of India lives in its villages," declared Mahatma Gandhi at the beginning of 20th century.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] According to the 2011 census of India, 69% of Indians (around 833 million people) live in villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Per the 2011 census of India, there were a total of 649,481 villages in India.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The size of these villages varies considerably.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] 236,004 Indian villages have a population of fewer than 500, while 3,976 villages have a population of 10,000+.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Most of the villages have their own temple, mosque, or church, or two and more than two of the above depending on the local religious following.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The majority of Pakistanis live in rural areas.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] According to the 2017 census, about 64% of the Pakistani population lives in rural areas.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Most rural areas in Pakistan tend to be near cities, and are peri-urban areas.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This is due to the definition of a rural area in Pakistan being an area that does not fall within an urban boundary.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A village is called deh or gaaon in Urdu.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Pakistani village life is marked by kinship and exchange relations.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Auyl (Kazakh: Ауыл) is a Kazakh word meaning "village" in Kazakhstan.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] According to the 2009 census of Kazakhstan, 42.7% of Kazakhstani citizens (7.5 million people) live in 8172 different villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] To refer to this concept along with the word "auyl" often used the Slavic word "selo" in Northern Kazakhstan.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In mainland China, villages are divisions under townships or towns.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the Republic of China (Taiwan), villages are divisions under townships or county-administered cities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The village is called a *tsuen* or *cūn* (村) under a rural township (鄉) and a *li* (里) under an urban township (鎮) or a county-controlled city.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Brunei, villages are officially the third- and lowest-level subdivisions of Brunei below districts and mukims.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A village is locally known by the Malay word *kampung* (also spelt as *kampong*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They may be villages in the traditional or anthropological sense but may also comprise delineated residential settlements, both rural and urban.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The community of a village is headed by a village head (Malay: *ketua kampung*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Communal infrastructure for the villagers may include a primary school, a religious school providing *ugama* or Islamic religious primary education which is compulsory for the Muslim pupils in the country, a mosque, and a community centre (Malay: *balai raya* or *dewan kemasyarakatan*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Indonesia, depending on the principles they are administered, villages are called *kampung* or *desa* (or *kelurahan* for those with urban functions).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A *desa* (a term that derives from a Sanskrit word meaning "country" that is found in the name "Bangladesh"=*bangla* and *desh/desha*) is administered according to traditions and customary law (*adat*), while a *kelurahan* is administered along more "modern" principles.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] *Desa* are generally located in rural areas while *kelurahan* are generally urban subdivisions.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A village head is respectively called *kepala desa* or *lurah*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Both are elected by the local community.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A *desa* or *kelurahan* is the subdivision of a *kecamatan* (district), in turn the subdivision of a *kabupaten* (regency) or *kota* (city).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The same general concept applies all over Indonesia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, there is some variation among the vast numbers of Austronesian ethnic groups.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] For instance, in Bali villages have been created by grouping traditional hamlets or *banjar*, which constitute the basis of Balinese social life.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the Minangkabau area in West Sumatra province, traditional villages are called *nagari* (a term deriving from another Sanskrit word meaning "city", which can be found in the name like "Srinagar"=*sri* and *nagar/nagari*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In some areas such as Tanah Toraja, elders take turns watching over the village at a command post.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] As a general rule, *desa* and *kelurahan* are groupings of hamlets (*kampung* in Indonesian, *dusun* in Javanese, *banjar* in Bali). a *kampung* is defined today as a village in Brunei and Indonesia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A Malay village typically contains a mosque or surau, paddy fields and Malay houses on stilts.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Malay and Indonesian villagers practice the culture of helping one another as a community, which is better known as "joint bearing of burdens" (*gotong royong*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They are family-oriented (especially the concept of respecting one's family [particularly the parents and elders]), courtesy and practice belief in God as paramount to everything else.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] It is common to see a cemetery near the mosque.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Sarawak and East Kalimantan, some villages are called 'long', primarily inhabited by the Orang Ulu.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Malaysian *kampung* were once aplenty in Singapore but there are almost no remaining *kampung* villages; the very few to have survived until today are mostly on outlying islands surrounding mainland Singapore, such as Pulau Ubin.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Mainland Singapore used to have many *kampung* villages but modern developments and rapid urbanisation works have seen them bulldozed away; Kampong Lorong Buangkok is the last surviving village on the country's mainland.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The term "kampung", sometimes spelled "kampong", is one of many Malay words to have entered common usage in Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Locally, the term is frequently used to refer to either one's hometown or a rural village, depending on the intended context.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In urban areas of the Philippines, the term "village" most commonly refers to private subdivisions, especially gated communities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] These villages emerged in the mid-20th century and were initially the domain of elite urban dwellers.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Those are common in major cities in the country and their residents have a wide range of income levels.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Such villages may or may not correspond to a barangay (the country's basic unit of government, also glossed as village), or be privately administered.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Barangays correspond more to precolonial villages; the chairman (formerly the village datu) now settles administrative, intrapersonal, and political matters or polices the area though with much less authority and respect than in Indonesia or Malaysia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages (làng) made up the basis of Vietnamese society.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Vietnamese village is considered one of the typical symbol of Asian agricultural production.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages in Vietnam typically contains: a village gate, bamboo hedges (lũy tre), a communal house where the tutelary deity (Thành hoàng) is worshiped, a well shared by the whole village, paddy fields (đồng lúa), temples (đền, chùa) and houses of all families in the village.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villagers share the same bloodline and are usually rice farmers, and may also share the same crafts.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Village have an important role in Vietnamese society (Vietnamese saying: "Custom rules the law" -"Phép vua thua lệ làng" [literally: the king's law yields to village customs]).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] It is common for Vietnamese villagers to prefer to be buried in their village upon death.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Another Slavic word for a village is *ves* (Polish: *wieś, wioska*; Czech: *ves, vesnice*; Slovak: *ves*; Slovene: *vas*; Russian: весь, romanized: *ves*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Slovenia, the word *selo* is used for very small villages (fewer than 100 people) and in dialects; the Slovene word *vas* is used all over Slovenia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Russia and Bulgaria, the word *ves* is archaic, but remains in idioms and locality names, such as Vesyegonsk and Belevehchevo.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The most commonly used word for village in Slovak is *dedina* (dialectical also *dzedzina*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The word's etymology may be (or may not be) rooted in the verb *dediť* ("to inherit"), referencing the inheriting of whole villages or properties within villages by noblemen or wealthy landowners.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Another etymology could be related to the Sanskrit word *deśá* (**देश**) similar to the Afghan *deh*, Bengal *desh* and Indonesian *desa*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The term *ves* appears in settlement names (mostly villages, but also some towns that evolved over time from villages).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The dialect term for village in east Slovakia is also *valal* (or *valala*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] *Dedina* is unrelated to the rarer east Slavic term *derevna*, which refers to a village with wooden (*derevo*) housing.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Bulgaria, the different types of *sela* vary from a small selo of 5 to 30 families to one of several thousand people.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] According to a 2002 census, in that year there were 2,385,000 Bulgarian citizens living in settlements classified as *villages*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Bulgaria, it is popular to visit villages for the atmosphere, culture, crafts, hospitality of the people and the surrounding nature.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This is called *selski turizam* (Bulgarian: селски туризъм), meaning "village tourism".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Russia, as of the 2010 Census, 26.3% of the country's population lives in rural localities; down from 26.7% recorded in the 2002 Census.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Multiple types of rural localities exist, but the two most common are *derevnya* (деревня) and *selo* (село).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Historically, the formal indication of status was religious: a city (*gorod*, город) had a cathedral, a *selo* had a church, while a *derevnya* had neither.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The lowest administrative unit of the Russian Empire, a *volost*, or its Soviet or modern Russian successor, a *selsoviet*, was typically headquartered in a *selo* and embraced a few neighboring villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the 1960s–1970s, the depopulation of the smaller villages was driven by the central planners' drive in order to get the farm workers out of smaller, "prospectless" hamlets and into the collective or state farms' main villages or even larger towns and cities, with more amenities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Most Russian rural residents are involved in agricultural work, and it is very common for villagers to produce their own food.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] As prosperous urbanites purchase village houses for their second homes, Russian villages sometimes are transformed into dacha settlements, used mostly for seasonal residence.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The historically Cossack regions of Southern Russia and parts of Ukraine, with their fertile soil and absence of serfdom, had a rather different pattern of settlement from central and northern Russia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] While peasants of central Russia lived in a village around the lord's manor, a Cossack family often lived on its own farm, called *khutor*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A number of such *khutors* plus a central village made up the administrative unit with a center in a *stanitsa* (Russian: станица, romanized: *stanitsa*; Ukrainian: станиця, romanized: *stanytsya*, lit.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Such *stanitsas*, often with a few thousand residents, were usually larger than a typical *selo* in central Russia.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Ukraine, a village (Ukrainian: село, romanized: *selo*, IPA: [seˈlɔ] ⓘ) is considered the lowest administrative unit.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages are under the jurisdiction of a hromada administration.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] There is another smaller type of rural settlement which is designated in Ukrainian as a *selyshche* (селище).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This type of community is often referred to in English as a "settlement".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the new law about populated places in Ukraine the term "selyshche", has a specific meaning.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the past the word "selyshche" was more ambiguous and there were distinction between rural *selyshche* and *selyshche miskoho typu* (urban-type settlement), abbreviated *smt* in Ukrainian.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The *khutir* (хутір) and *stanytsia* (станиця) are not part of the administrative division any longer, primarily due to collectivization.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] *Khutirs* were very small rural localities consisting of just few housing units and were sort of individual farms.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They became really popular during the Stolypin reform in the early 20th century.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] During the collectivization, however, residents of such settlements were usually declared to be kulaks and had all their property confiscated and distributed to others (nationalized) without any compensation.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The *stanitsa* likewise has not survived as an administrative term.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The *stanitsa* was a type of a collective community that could include one or more settlements such as villages, *khutirs*, and others.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Today, *stanitsa*-type formations have only survived in Kuban (Russian Federation) where Ukrainians were resettled during the time of the Russian Empire.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A *shtetl* (plural *shtetlekh*) was a small market town or village with a majority Jewish population in central and eastern Europe.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The word *shtetl* is Yiddish, derived from the word *shtot* (town) with the suffix *-l*, a diminutive.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Shtetlekh first began to appear in the 13th century, and were characteristic aspects of Jewish life in central and Eastern Europe until the 1940s.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The shtetl occupies an important place in Jewish collective memory (particularly the history of Ashkenazi Jews) and has been depicted extensively in literature, visual art, theatre, and film, including such examples as the writing of Mendele Mocher Sforim, Isaac Bashevis Singer, and Sholem Aleichem.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Sholem Aleichem's Tevye the Dairyman stories, set in the fictional shtetl of Anatevka, were eventually adapted into the Fiddler on the Roof stage play (which itself was later adapted for film).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] During the Holocaust, most shtetlekh were depopulated of their Jewish communities through mass deportations or liquidations.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Many are memorialized in yizkor books, written testimonies that describe the histories of Jewish communities destroyed during the Holocaust.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Thus, identifiers no longer change after municipal mergers or areal transfers, and it is no longer possible to determine which land register village an estate is located on based solely on its identifier.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] While land register villages developed from land ownership within and around actual settlements during the Great Partition, later on they no longer had any direct connection to actual place names, with local definitions of villages often differing from land register villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A commune in Group 3 or 4 is considered as a village (*commune rurale*).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] An independent association named *Les Plus Beaux Villages de France* (affiliated to the international association The Most Beautiful Villages in the World), was created in 1982 to promote assets of small and picturesque French villages of quality heritage.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] As of July 2023, 172 villages in France have been listed in "The Most Beautiful Villages of France".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Germany a *Dorf* (village) usually consists of at least a few houses but can have up to a few thousand inhabitants.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Larger villages can also be referred to as a *Flecken* or *Markt* depending on the region and the settlement's market rights.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Smaller villages usually do not have their own government.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Instead, they are part (*Ortsteil*) of the municipality of a nearby town.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the settlement geography typology in Germany, a distinction is made between individual settlements and group settlements.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Only group settlements of a certain size ("large group settlement") are referred to as villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The size that a settlement must have in order to be considered a village varies from region to region.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Only settlements in rural areas are referred to as villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Ideal villages were traditionally characterized by agriculture, most of the inhabitants were farmers or agricultural workers, the settlement form was determined by the farmhouses and was closely connected to the surrounding farmland, the meadow and the traditional land forms.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In addition, the majority of the population used to live in rural settlements, whereas today only a small proportion still does.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Whereas in the German Reich in 1900, almost half (46%) of the population lived in rural areas, the proportion in the Federal Republic of Germany had fallen to around a quarter (23%) by 2015.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Italy, villages are spread throughout the country.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] No legal definition of village exists in Italian law; nonetheless, a settlement inhabited by less than 2000 people is usually described as "village".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] More often, Italian villages that are a part of a municipality are called *frazione*, whereas the village that hosts the municipal seat is called *paese* (town) or *capoluogo*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Its motto is *Il fascino dell'Italia nascosta* ("The charm of hidden Italy").
[src:bandung/administrative-village] As of November 2023, 361 villages in Italy have been listed in "The Most Beautiful Villages of Italy".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The association organizes initiatives within the villages, such as festivals, exhibitions, fetes, conferences and concerts that highlight the cultural, historical, gastronomic and linguistic heritage, involving residents, schools, and local artists.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The club promotes numerous initiatives on the international market.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In 2016, the association signed a global agreement with ENIT, to promote tourism in the most beautiful villages in the world.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In 2017, the club signed an agreement with Costa Cruises for the enhancement of some villages, which are offered to cruise passengers arriving in Italian ports aboard the operator's ships.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Spain, a village (*pueblo*) refers to a small population unit, smaller than a town (*villa* [an archaic term that survives only in official uses, such as the official name of Spain's capital, "la Villa de Madrid"]) and a city (*ciudad*), typically located in a rural environment.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] While commonly it is the smallest administrative unit (*municipio*), it is possible for a village to be legally composed of smaller population units in its territory.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] There is not a clear-cut distinction between villages, towns and cities in Spain, since they had been traditionally categorized according to their religious importance and their relationship with surrounding population units.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages (*aldeias*, singular: *aldeia*) are more usual in the northern and central regions, Azores Islands and in the Alentejo.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Most of them have a church and a *Casa do Povo* (people's house), where the village's summer *romarias* or religious festivities are usually held.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Summer is also when many villages are host to a range of folk festivals and fairs, taking advantage of the fact that many of the locals who reside abroad tend to come back to their native village for the holidays.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the flood-prone districts of the Netherlands, particularly in the northern provinces of Friesland and Groningen, villages were traditionally built on low man-made hills called terpen before the introduction of regional dyke-systems.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] "village") is usually applied to settlements no larger than 20,000, though there's no official law regarding status of settlements in the Netherlands.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A village in the UK is a compact settlement of houses, smaller in size than a town, and generally based on agriculture or, in some areas, mining (such as Ouston, County Durham), quarrying or sea fishing.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They are very similar to those in Ireland.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The major factors in the type of settlement are: location of water sources, organization of agriculture and landholding, and likelihood of flooding.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] For example, in areas such as the Lincolnshire Wolds, the villages are often found along the spring line halfway down the hillsides, and originate as spring line settlements, with the original open field systems around the village.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In northern Scotland, most villages are planned to a grid pattern located on or close to major roads, whereas in areas such as the Forest of Arden, woodland clearances produced small hamlets around village greens.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Because of the topography of the Clent Hills the north Worcestershire village of Clent is an example of a village with no centre but instead consists of series of hamlets scattered on and around the Hills.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Some villages have disappeared (for example, deserted medieval villages), sometimes leaving behind a church or manor house and sometimes nothing but bumps in the fields.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Some show archaeological evidence of settlement at three or four different layers, each distinct from the previous one.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Clearances may have been to accommodate sheep or game estates, or enclosure, or may have resulted from depopulation, such as after the Black Death or following a move of the inhabitants to more prosperous districts.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Other villages have grown and merged and often form hubs within the general mass of suburbia—such as Hampstead, London and Didsbury in Manchester.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Many villages are now predominantly dormitory locations and have suffered the loss of shops, churches and other facilities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] For many British people, the village represents an ideal of Great Britain.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Seen as being far from the bustle of modern life, it is represented as quiet and harmonious, if a little inward-looking.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This concept of an unspoilt Arcadia is present in many popular representations of the village such as the radio serial *The Archers* or the best kept village competitions.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Many villages in South Yorkshire, north Nottinghamshire, north east Derbyshire, County Durham, South Wales and Northumberland are known as pit villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] These (such as Murton, County Durham) grew from hamlets when the sinking of a colliery in the early 20th century resulted in a rapid growth in their population and the colliery owners built new housing, shops, pubs and churches.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Some pit villages outgrew nearby towns by area and population; for example, Rossington in South Yorkshire came to have over four times more people than the nearby town of Bawtry.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Some pit villages grew to become towns; for example, Maltby in South Yorkshire grew from 600 people in the 19th century to over 17,000 in 2007.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Maltby was constructed under the auspices of the Sheepbridge Coal and Iron Company and included ample open spaces and provision for gardens.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the UK, the main historical distinction between a hamlet and a village was that the latter had a church, and so usually was the centre of worship for an ecclesiastical parish.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, some civil parishes may contain more than one village.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The typical village had a pub or inn, shops, and a blacksmith.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] But many of these facilities are now gone, and many villages are dormitories for commuters.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The population of such settlements ranges from a few hundred people to around five thousand.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Like France, villages in Lebanon are usually located in remote mountainous areas.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The majority of villages in Lebanon retain their Aramaic names or are derivative of the Aramaic names, and this is because Aramaic was still in use in Mount Lebanon up to the 18th century.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The district of Danniyeh consists of thirty-six small villages, which includes Almrah, Kfirchlan, Kfirhbab, Hakel al Azimah, Siir, Bakhoun, Miryata, Assoun, Sfiiri, Kharnoub, Katteen, Kfirhabou, Zghartegrein, Ein Qibil.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Danniyeh (known also as Addinniyeh, Al Dinniyeh, Al Danniyeh, Arabic: سير الضنية) is a region located in Miniyeh-Danniyeh District in the North Governorate of Lebanon.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The region lies east of Tripoli, extends north as far as Akkar District, south to Bsharri District and Zgharta District and as far east as Baalbek and Hermel.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Dinniyeh has an excellent ecological environment filled with woodlands, orchards and groves.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Several villages are located in this mountainous area, the largest town being Sir Al Dinniyeh.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] An example of a typical mountainous Lebanese village in Dannieh would be Hakel al Azimah which is a small village that belongs to the district of Danniyeh, situated between Bakhoun and Assoun's boundaries.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] It is in the centre of the valleys that lie between the Arbeen Mountains and the Khanzouh.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Syria contains a large number of villages that vary in size and importance, including the ancient, historical and religious villages, such as Ma'loula, Sednaya, and Brad (Mar Maroun's time).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The diversity of the Syrian environments creates significant differences between the Syrian villages in terms of the economic activity and the method of adoption.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages in the south of Syria (Hauran, Jabal al-Druze), the north-east (the Syrian island) and the Orontes River basin depend mostly on agriculture, mainly grain, vegetables, and fruits.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages in the region of Damascus and Aleppo depend on trading.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Some other villages, such as Marmarita depend heavily on tourist activity.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Mediterranean cities in Syria, such as Tartus and Latakia have similar types of villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Mainly, villages were built in very good sites which had the fundamentals of the rural life, like water.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] An example of a Mediterranean Syrian village in Tartus would be al-Annazah, which is a small village that belongs to the area of al-Sauda.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The area of al-Sauda is called a *nahiya*.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In contrast to the Old World, the concept of village in Canada and the United States today is largely disconnected from its rural and communal origins.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The situation is different in Mexico because of its large bulk of indigenous population living in traditional villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] It is believed that the name Canada may be a transliteration of the Iroquoisan word for "village".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Jacques Cartier was given directions to the Kanata of Kebec and it became the name of the French Colonial district before it was the nation's name.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In twenty U.S. states, the term "village" refers to a specific form of incorporated municipal government, similar to a city but with less authority and geographic scope.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, this is a generality; in many states, there are villages that are an order of magnitude larger than the smallest cities in the state.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The distinction is not necessarily based on population, but on the relative powers granted to the different types of municipalities and correspondingly, different obligations to provide specific services to residents.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In some states such as New York and Michigan, a village is an incorporated municipality, within a single town or civil township.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In some cases, the village may be coterminous with the town or township, in which case the two may have a consolidated government.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] There are also villages that span the boundaries of more than one town or township; some villages may straddle county borders.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] There is no population limit to villages in New York.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Hempstead, the largest village, has 55,000 residents, making it more populous than some of the state's cities.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, villages in the state may not exceed five square miles (13 km2) in area.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Michigan and Illinois also have no set population limit for villages and there are many villages that are larger than cities in those states.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The village of Schaumburg, Illinois had 78,723 residents as of the 2020 census.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A village also has no written figure against how small a population can be, with the United States' smallest incorporated village being Dering Harbor, NY, with a population of just over 10.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Michigan, a village is always legally part of a township.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages can incorporate land in multiple townships and even multiple counties.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The largest village in the state is Beverly Hills in Southfield Township which had a population of 10,267 people as of the 2010 census.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the state of Wisconsin, a village is always legally separate from the towns that it has been incorporated from.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The largest village is Menomonee Falls, which has over 32,000 residents.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Pennsylvania law, the term borough is used to refer to the same type of entity.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] 80% of Pennsylvania's 956 boroughs have populations of less than 5,000 but about thirty have populations of over 10,000 with State College having more than 40,000 residents.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Ohio villages are usually legally part of the township from which they were incorporated, although exceptions such as Hiram exist, in which the village is separate from the township.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages become cities if they grow to a population of at least 5,000.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Maryland, a locality designated "Village of ..." may be either an incorporated town or a special tax district.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] An example of the latter is the Village of Friendship Heights.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In North Carolina, the only difference between cities, towns, and villages is the term itself.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In many states, the term "village" is used to refer to a relatively small unincorporated community, similar to a hamlet in New York state.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] This informal usage may be found even in states that have villages as an incorporated municipality, although such usage might be considered incorrect and confusing.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In most New England states, a "village" is a center of population or trade, including the town center, in an otherwise sparsely developed town or city — for instance, the village of Hyannis in the town of Barnstable, Massachusetts.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, in Vermont and Connecticut, both incorporated and unincorporated villages exist.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Villages in Nigeria vary significantly because of cultural and geographical differences.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In the North, villages were under traditional rulers long before the Jihad of Shaikh Uthman Bin Fodio and after the Holy War.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] At that time Traditional rulers used to have absolute power in their administrative regions.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] After Dan Fodio's Jihad in 1804, political structure of the North became Islamic where emirs were the political, administrative and spiritual leaders of their people.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] These emirs appointed a number of people to assist them in running the administration and that included villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Every Hausa village was reigned by Magaji (Village head) who was answerable to his Hakimi (mayor) at the town level.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] The Magaji also had his cabinet who assisted him in ruling his village efficiently, among whom was Mai-Unguwa (Ward Head).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] With the creation of Native Authority in Nigerian provinces, the autocratic power of village heads along with all other traditional rulers was subdued hence they ruled 'under the guidance of colonial officials'.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Even though the constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria has not recognised the functions of traditional rulers, they still command respect in their villages and political office holders liaise with them almost every time to reach people.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In Hausa language, village is called *ƙauye* and every local government area is made up of several small and large *ƙauyuka* (villages).
[src:bandung/administrative-village] For instance, Girka is a village in Kaita town in Katsina state in Nigeria.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They have mud houses with thatched roofing though, like in most of the villages in the North, zinc roofing has become a common sight.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Still in many villages in the North, people do not have access to potable water.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] So they fetch water from ponds and streams.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Others are lucky to have wells within a walking distance.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Women rush in the morning to fetch water in their clay pots from wells, boreholes and streams.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] However, the government is now providing them with water bore holes.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Electricity and GSM network are reaching more and more villages in the North almost every day.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] So bad feeder roads may lead to remote villages with electricity and unstable GSM network.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] Village dwellers in the Southeastern region lived separately in "clusters of huts belonging to the patrilinage".
[src:bandung/administrative-village] As the rainforest region is dominated by Igbo speaking people, the villages are called *ime obodo* (inside town) in Igbo language.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] A typical large village might have a few thousand persons who shared the same market, meeting place and beliefs.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] In South Africa the majority of people in rural areas reside in villages.
[src:bandung/administrative-village] They vary in size from having a population of less than 500 to roughly 2000.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Al-Jabbar, meaning The Compeller in Arabic, is one of the 99 names of Allah.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] "Aljabar" is the Indonesian word for algebra, which was founded by a Muslim.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Coincidentally, "Jabar" is also an acronym for Jawa Barat and a nickname for the province of West Java; thus, the name Masjid Al Jabbar or Al Jabar can also be translated as "Mosque in West Java" or "West Java Mosque".
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] In the past, the Gedebage area was a swamp called Muras Geger Hanjuang.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] These swamps are the remnants of the Ancient Bandung Lake.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] At the end of the 19th century, these swamps began to dry up and become rice fields.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] The state railway company, Staatsspoorwegen (SS), built a railway connecting Bandung and Cicalengka in the middle of these swamps.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Gedebage became a sub-district after the city of Bandung was divided in 2006.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] This expansion made this area lively because people started building new housing there.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Construction of the mosque started on 29, December, 2017.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Ex-governor Ahmad Heryawan and ex-vice governor Deddy Mizwar performed the ground breaking ceremony and laid the first stone to officially begin construction of the mosque.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, construction was halted in 2020 and was later resumed one and a half years later on 24 August 2021.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] After 5 years of construction, the mosque was officially inaugurated on 30 December 2022 by Governor Ridwan Kamil.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] The Mosque covers a total area of 21,799,20 square meters.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] It has a ground floor that covers an area of 11,238.20 square meters, the first floor has an area of 8,329 square meters, and the mezzanine floor has an area of 2,232 square meters.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Meanwhile, the area devoted to lakes and reservoirs is 6,930 hectares, and the area devoted to parking lots, plazas, and green spaces is 11,163 hectares.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] The prayer chambers can accommodate 9,822 people on the first floor, 3,188 on the mezzanine floor, 3,627 in the halls, and 16,363 on the courtyard.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] The mosque contains four 99-meter-tall minarets, one in each of its four corners.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] 6,136 sheets of glass are designed to mimic fish scales that make up the facade and dome.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] There are 27 entrances to the mosque, representing the 27 cities or regencies of West Java.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] On each of these entrances there is a batik motif which is native to each of the cities or regencies.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Turkish-woven carpets are used for the floors of the mosque.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] Given that the mosque is situated in the flood-prone district of Gedebage, it is surrounded by a 6.9 hectare reservoir that can absorb water during floods.
[src:bandung/al-jabbar-grand-mosque] The mosque has a garden and a museum dedicated to Islam.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Born on 13 December 1897 in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, Albert Aalbers was the youngest son of Theo Aalbers and Johanna Buis.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Between 1910 and 1918, Aalbers studied architecture at the Rotterdam Academy of Visual Arts and Techniques.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] At that time Dutch architecture was highly influenced by the expressionist movement due to popular expressionist artists, including the painter Willem de Kooning who also studied in the same school.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] In 1923, Albert Aalbers and his brother, Theo, established the Gebroeder Aalbers architecture office in Rotterdam.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Their projects ranged from offices to villas.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The famous American architect, Frank Lloyd Wright, influenced their works; the Villa Dijkendam—owned by Albert Aalbers' future father-in-law's family—is one such example of a building inspired by Wright's works.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] 1926 was a difficult time for the Aalbers brother during which they filed for bankruptcy and closed down their office.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] His brother migrated to the Dutch Indies—the Netherlands colony—while Albert remained to try his luck again by opening an office in Hengelo, in the east of the Netherlands.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He married Anna Marie Philipina Lieuwen in 1928 and the couple migrated to the Dutch Indies.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] At the beginning of their stay, Albert Aalbers worked in a contractor's office owned by J.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] In 1930 the Aalbers family moved to Bandung, a few kilometers east of Sukabumi.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] At that time, the Dutch East Indies government was planning to move the colonial capital from Batavia (present-day Jakarta) to Bandung.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The plan was never realized although it transformed Bandung into a city of new European ambience, including its built environment.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Several Dutch architects, including Thomas Karsten, Henri Maclaine-Pont, J Gerber and C.P.W.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Schoemaker, were actively involved designing and renovating buildings throughout the city.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Aalbers saw this as a good opportunity and he started to work as a freelance architect in the city.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Later he and his friend, Rijk de Waal, opened a new firm, the Aalbers en De Waal.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] In 1935 the Aalbers en De Waal office received a contract to design an office building for the DENIS Bank (*De Eerste Nederlandsch-Indische Spaarkas* or the First Dutch-Indies Savings).
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Aalbers used steel materials for the building structure and concrete floors, but he designed the horizontal side with smooth curves as if the materials were made from plastic.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] As a point of visual contrast, Aalbers put a lift tower in the middle of the building, higher than the six rounded platforms.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] This articulation point of vertical tower against the horizontal smoothness provides an impression of disrupting the elasticity.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Rounded façades with mainly purely decorative non-functional elements are similar to the Amsterdam School style, but Aalbers was a follower of the International style or modernist architecture that believed form should simply follow function and eschew such decoration.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] One pioneer of modernist architecture, Le Corbusier, famous for facades of open space, inspired Aalbers in his designs for the interior of the DENIS bank.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The ground floor contains a staircase with glass window leading to a public place, while the second floor is used as offices with large terraces facing Naripan street.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The DENIS bank design was highly appreciated after which their office received another contract in 1936 to redesign the famous hotel in Bandung, the Savoy Homann Hotel.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The hotel was built in 1880 and had been the major accommodation for the wealthy.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] F Van Es Jr., the hotel owner, asked Aalbers to renovate the hotel with a similar elastic impression as in the DENIS bank.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The ocean wave facade and the vertical tower in the middle thus decorate the hotel's exterior, while Aalbers kept the colonial classical style for the interior.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The hotel was reopened in 1939 and became internationally renowned.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Several Hollywood artists have stayed in the hotel, including Charlie Chaplin and Mary Pickford.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] On the recommendation of Van Es Jr., Aalbers' office received more contracts to design hotels.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He renovated the hotel lobby of the Grand Hotel Lembang at Lembang, a hillside village north of Bandung.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He also designed a new hotel, the Grand Hotel Ngamplang at Garut, and a resort hotel in the middle of the Pangalengan tea plantation in the south of Bandung.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Apart from designing office and hotel, Aalbers was known for his unique villa designs.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He designed three identical villas at Juanda Street, known as "the locomotive", in 1937, which were built as a promotion for the new residential area in the north of Bandung.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] A unique character inside each of the villa is a stair room as an entrance to the asymmetric villa.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] During his period in Bandung between 1931–1942, Aalbers designed twelve identical villas at the Pager Gunung Street (1939), fourteen houses at Haji Hasan Street (1940) and the three-colors (*de driekleur*) villa at Juanda Street.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The Three-colors Villa was his last work in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The Netherlands was on the brink of World War II and the Dutch Indies was occupied by Imperial Japan.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] The Japanese Occupation Army sent Aalbers and his family to the Dutch intern camp in Cimahi and then were transferred to the Jatinegara camp in Jakarta.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Even during his captivity he drew many sketches, including his dream of having a villa in a tropical environment with mountains in the background.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] In 1946, Aalbers, his wife and his two daughters moved to Amsterdam.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He opened a new architecture office with the name of 'Aalbers en De Waal, Architecten, Amsterdam-Bandoeng'.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] He put 'Bandoeng' in the name as a wish that someday he would be able to return to Bandung.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] His hope wasn't realized due to poor health and the unstable political circumstances in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Much of his work still stands in Bandung, such as the DENIS bank and the Savoy Homann Hotel.
[src:bandung/albert-aalbers] Some villas he designed have been destroyed during the war and also damaged due to subsequent renovations.
[src:bandung/alluvial] The present consensus is that "alluvium" refers to loose sediments of all types deposited by running water in floodplains or in alluvial fans or related landforms.
[src:bandung/alluvial] However, the meaning of the term has varied considerably since it was first defined in the French dictionary of Antoine Furetière, posthumously published in 1690.
[src:bandung/alluvial] Drawing upon concepts from Roman law, Furetière defined *alluvion* (the French term for alluvium) as new land formed by deposition of sediments along rivers and seas.
[src:bandung/alluvial] By the 19th century, the term had come to mean recent sediments deposited by rivers on top of older *diluvium*, which was similar in character but interpreted as sediments deposited by Noah's flood.
[src:bandung/alluvial] With the rejection by geologists of the concept of a primordial universal flood, the term "diluvium" fell into disfavor and was replaced with "older alluvium".
[src:bandung/alluvial] At the same time, the term "alluvium" came to mean all sediment deposits due to running water on plains.
[src:bandung/alluvial] The definition gradually expanded to include deposits in estuaries, coasts, and young rock of marine and fluvial origin.
[src:bandung/alluvial] Alluvium and diluvium were grouped as *colluvium* in the late 19th century.
[src:bandung/alluvial] "Colluvium" is now generally understood as sediments produced by gravity-driven transport on steep slopes.
[src:bandung/alluvial] At the same time, the definition of "alluvium" has switched back to an emphasis on sediments deposited by river action.
[src:bandung/alluvial] There continues to be disagreement over what other sediment deposits should be included under the term "alluvium".
[src:bandung/alluvial] Most alluvium is Quaternary in age and is often referred to as "cover" because these sediments obscure the underlying bedrock.
[src:bandung/alluvial] Most sedimentary material that fills a basin ("basin fill") that is not lithified is typically lumped together as "alluvial".
[src:bandung/alluvial] Alluvium of Pliocene age occurs, for example, in parts of Idaho.
[src:bandung/alluvial] Alluvium of late Miocene age occurs, for example, in the valley of the San Joaquin River, California.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The origin of the term "Ambon" is not easily determined.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] According to local accounts, the term is derived from the word embun (mist/dew).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The mountain peaks on Ambon Island are frequently covered by thick mist.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The term Laha was also once used to name the Fort of **Nossa Senhora da Anunciada**, which became the precursor of the settlement.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Although the term "Ambon" now refers to Ambon City, Ambon Island, or the Ambonese people, throughout history (especially in the 20th century), it referred to the inhabitants of Central Maluku.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The phrase "Ambonese people" (Ambonezen) itself referred to the residents of Central Maluku, even though it was originally only used for the inhabitants of Ambon City who possessed a mestizo culture.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon City began to develop following the arrival of the Portuguese in 1513.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Later, around 1575, Portuguese authorities mobilized the local population to build the Kota Laha Fort (also known as the Ferangi Fort), which was originally named Nossa Senhora da Anunciada, located on the Honipopu Plain.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] During its construction, the workers established village-like organizations such as Soya, which became the foundation of Ambon City.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] This was because, in its subsequent development, these groups evolved into an organized territorial genealogical society.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] After the Dutch successfully seized the Maluku Islands and specifically Ambon from Portuguese control, the **Nossa Senhora de Anunciada** fort was captured in 1605 and turned into the center of colonial administration under the name Victoria.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Following a severe earthquake that caused heavy damage, the fort was renovated and renamed Nieuw Victoria, though it remained better known among locals as Fort Victoria.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] This fort is historically significant as the site where the national hero Pattimura was executed by hanging on 16 December 1817.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon Island was conquered by the Dutch East India Company (VOC) on 23 February 1605, with military assistance from Ternate, Luhu, Hitu and Gowa.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] During the early VOC era, several governors held power, including the authoritarian Adrian Martensz Block, who utilized forced labor to expand Fort Victoria, and Herman van Speult, who oppressed the people through spice trade monopolies.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] On 17 February 1796, the VOC surrendered to British Admiral Pieter Ramier, making Ambon part of British territory until 1803.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Afterward, control was handed back to the Dutch government (rather than the VOC, which had gone bankrupt in 1799).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] During the Dutch East Indies era, Ambon underwent modernization.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Fort Victoria became the capital of the Government of Amboina, part of the Government der Molukken established in 1817.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] On 7 September 1921, the people of Ambon were granted equal rights to the colonial government, marking a political victory for the local struggle and allowing them to play a role in governance.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Japanese troops landed in Ambon on 1 February 1942.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] They defeated the Dutch and their allies in the Battle of Ambon to seize the city, which served as a strategic naval and air base.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] During this occupation, citizens suffered from poverty and famine due to the war.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Remnants of this era can still be found today, such as the Ambon War Cemetery for Allied soldiers and Japanese torpedoes discovered at the bottom of Ambon Bay.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The anniversary of Ambon City was officially set as 7 September 1575.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] This date was determined during a 1972 seminar involving Pattimura University.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The year 1575 commemorates the start of the construction of Fort Kota Laha, while the date 7 September honors the day in 1921 when Ambon citizens achieved equal political rights.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city's anniversary was first celebrated on 7 September 1973.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Most of the land area can be classified as hilly to steeply sloping, while 17% of the land area can be classified as more flat or shallow-sloped.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon experiences a tropical rainforest climate (*Af*) according to the Köppen climate classification as there is no real dry season.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The driest month is November with total precipitation of 114 mm (4.5 in), while the wettest month is June with total precipitation of 638 mm (25.1 in).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] As it is located near the equator, the temperature throughout the year is constant.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The hottest month is December, with an average temperature of 27.2 °C (81 °F), while the coolest month is July, with an average temperature 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon City was established under Law Number 60 of 1958, enacted on 17 July 1958.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] It is part of the Maluku Province and holds the status of a city in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Similar to other Indonesian cities, its administration is divided into three levels: city, district (kecamatan), and sub-district (kelurahan) or village (desa).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] As part of the Maluku Islands, some villages in the city are also known by the traditional term negeri.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city administration is led by a Mayor who is accountable to the Ambon City Regional House of Representatives (DPRD), in accordance with Government Regulation Number 108 of 2000.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Both the Mayor and Vice Mayor are based at the Ambon City Hall.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The administration is also supported by the DPRD, whose members are elected by the people.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Administratively, Ambon is divided into 5 districts, which are further subdivided into 50 sub-districts and villages.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The largest district is Sirimau, with a population of 178,611, while the smallest is South Leitimur, with 11,862 residents (as of 2016).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The Mayor serves as the highest leader within the Ambon City government.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The Mayor of Ambon is titled Upu Latu Lette Kota Nusa Yapono, where Nusa Yapono refers to the traditional name given to the city by the community.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Currently, the city is led by Mayor Bodewin Wattimena and Vice Mayor Elly Toisutta, who won the 2024 Ambon Mayoral Election.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city is divided into five districts (*kecamatan*), tabulated below with their areas and their 2010 Census and 2020 Census populations, together with the official estimates as at mid 2024.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The table also includes the locations of the district administrative centres, the number of administrative villages and subdistricts (*kelurahan*) in each district (totaling 20 urban *kelurahan*, 20 *negari* and 10 rural *desa*), and its post codes.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Notes: (a) comprising 8 *kelurahan* and 5 *negeri*.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] (b) comprising 10 *kelurahan*, 3 *negeri* and one *desa*.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] (c) comprising 1 *kelurahan*, 2 *negeri* and 4 *desa*.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] (d) comprising 1 *kelurahan*, 2 *negeri* and 5 *desa*.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Like other regions in the (Maluku Islands), areas in Ambon are still considered to have the status of states, led by kings and queens.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] According to the Regional Office of the Ministry of Religious Affairs for Maluku Province, as of 2022, the largest religious group in Ambon City is Christian at 59.41%, consisting of Protestants (56.93%) and Catholics (2.48%).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] This is followed by Islam at 40.47%, Hinduism at 0.08%, Buddhism at 0.34%, and Confucianism and others at less than 0.01%.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] In 2021, there were 294 Protestant churches and 39 Catholic churches in the city.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The largest Protestant church building is GPM Maranatha, while the largest Catholic church is the Saint Francis Xavier Cathedral.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Additionally, GPM Silo serves as one of the city's primary Protestant churches.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The majority of the city's Protestant community are members of the Protestant Church of Maluku (GPM).
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon also has its own Roman Catholic diocese, the Diocese of Amboina.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The districts with a Christian majority are Nusaniwe, Baguala, and South Leitimur, where Protestantism is the dominant religion.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city also has a large Muslim population, accounting for 40.47% of residents based on 2022 data.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] In 2021, there were 168 mosques; one of the largest is the Al-Fatah Grand Mosque, while the oldest is the Ambon Jami Mosque, built in 1860.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon City is also the largest contributor of Hajj pilgrims in Maluku, with 245 pilgrims in 2014.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The districts where Islam is the dominant religion are Sirimau and Ambon Bay.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon City also has other minority religious populations in very small numbers, namely Hinduism, Buddhism, and Confucianism.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Although their numbers are small, these three religions receive government attention.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] In 2018, President Joko Widodo inaugurated the Hindu Center and Buddha Center in Ambon City.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] This was done to fulfill the Maluku Governor's wish for Maluku to become a laboratory for religious harmony in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] A well-known temple (pura) in the city is Pura Stana Giri Ciwa, while the famous Buddhist temple (wihara) is Wihara Swarna Giri Tirta.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city also has a very small number of Confucian followers, recorded as 7 individuals in the 2010 Indonesian Population Census.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Economic growth rate of Ambon City in 2014 was 5.96%.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Gross Domestic Regional Product in 2014 both at current market price and at constant market price was increasing gradually.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The increase, if compared to 2013 GDRP at current market price equal to 12.76 percent and 5.96 percent for GDRP at constant market price.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The GDRP at current market price in Ambon 2014 was equal to Rp.9.9 trillion, whereas for GDRP at constant 2010 market price, it was equal to Rp.7.77 trillion.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] In 2014, the gross domestic product per capita of Ambon based on current prices grew by 8.3 percent, while for the constant price in Ambon City grew by 1.7 percent.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The poverty rate in the city of Ambon is 4.42% which is the smallest percentage of poverty in the province of Maluku.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] All twenty one economic sectors in 2014 saw positive growth for GDRP of Ambon.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] For GDRP at current market price, the highest contribution was provided by the electricity and gas Sector with 34.2 percent, while the lowest was human health and Social Work activities with 6.61 percent.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Education in Ambon City was recorded to have begun with the establishment of MULO in 1947, a Secondary School in 1946, and the Algemeene Middelbare School in 1946.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Thus, in these two aspects, the city has matched other developed nations.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon is home to several prominent higher education institutions located in the city, such as Pattimura University (Unpatti) and Ambon State Polytechnic, both situated in Ambon Bay.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Although the city's higher education institutions are not among the best in Indonesia, the two best universities mentioned are still categorized in Cluster 3, with Ambon State Polytechnic ranked 186th and Pattimura University ranked 282nd according to Kemenristekdikti.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Efforts to improve education have also been carried out through various programs, including scholarships.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] The city government has provided study scholarships to Japan for students—distributed across Maebashi, Fukuoka, and other cities in collaboration with the Kyoto government—and to India for civil servants.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] However, there was a case of a master's degree scholarship scam that victimized a Unpatti student, though it did not originate from the government.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon has many natural tourist attractions, though administratively, most of the highly famous sites are located in the Central Maluku Regency but are accessed through Ambon City.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Among the beaches on Ambon Island, the most famous is Natsepa Beach, located in Suli Village, Central Maluku, which is well-known for its rujak natsepa.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Additionally, there is Liang Beach, situated in Liang, Sala Hutu, Central Maluku.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] For diving activities, there is Nusa Pombo, an island located between Ambon Island and Haruku Island.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] On the other hand, famous tourist spots within the city's administrative area are fewer and not as renowned as those in the regency, yet they are no less beautiful.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Among the most famous is Pintu Kota Beach.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Pintu Kota Beach is famous for its uniqueness, featuring a large hole that pierces through a coral cliff, passing through both sides.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] There is also Namasua Beach located in Naku, which remains relatively unknown.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Besides beaches, there is Anihang Waterfall in Naku, which was once mentioned by Mayor Richard.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] In Ambon City, there is a museum called Museum Siwalima.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Inside the Museum Siwalima, there are collections of historical objects.
[src:bandung/ambon-maluku] Ambon is served by Pattimura International Airport.
[src:bandung/bandung] The Dutch first established tea plantations around the mountains in the 18th century, and a road was constructed to connect the plantation area to the colonial capital Batavia (180 kilometres (112 miles) to the northwest).
[src:bandung/bandung] In the early 20th century, the Dutch inhabitants of Bandung demanded the establishment of a municipality (*gemeente*), which was granted in 1906, and Bandung gradually developed into a resort city for plantation owners.
[src:bandung/bandung] Luxurious hotels, restaurants, cafés, and European boutiques were opened, leading the city to be nicknamed *Parijs van Java* (Dutch: *"The Paris of Java"*).
[src:bandung/bandung] After Indonesia declared independence in 1945, the city experienced ongoing development and urbanization, transforming from an idyllic town into a dense 16,500 people/km2 (per square kilometer) metropolitan area with living space for over 8 million people.
[src:bandung/bandung] New skyscrapers, high-rise buildings, bridges, and gardens have been constructed.
[src:bandung/bandung] Natural resources have been heavily exploited, particularly by conversion of the protected upland area into highland villas and real estate.
[src:bandung/bandung] Although the city has encountered many problems (ranging from waste disposal and floods to a complicated traffic system resulting from a lack of road infrastructure), it still attracts large numbers of tourists, weekend sightseers, and migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 2017 the city won a regional environmental sustainability award for having the cleanest air among major cities in ASEAN.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city is also known as a Smart City, leveraging technology to improve government services and social media that alert residents to issues such as floods or traffic jams.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city is part of the UNESCO Creative Cities Network, which it joined in 2015.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is Indonesia's major technology centre.
[src:bandung/bandung] The first Asian-African Conference, the Bandung Conference, was hosted in Bandung by President Sukarno in 1955 and is now a decennial event.
[src:bandung/bandung] Redevelopment of the existing Husein Sastranegara International Airport (BDO) was completed in 2016.
[src:bandung/bandung] The new larger second airport for Greater Bandung - Kertajati International Airport (KJT) - opened in June 2018, just in time for the 2018 Asian Games.
[src:bandung/bandung] The official name of the city during the colonial Dutch East Indies period was **Bandoeng**.
[src:bandung/bandung] The earliest reference to the area dates back to 1488, although archaeological findings suggest a type of *Homo erectus* species had long previously lived on the banks of the Cikapundung River and around the old lake of Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] During the 17th and 18th centuries, the Dutch East Indies Company (VOC) established plantations in the Bandung area.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1786, a supply road connecting Batavia (now Jakarta), Bogor, Cianjur, Bandung, Sumedang and Cirebon was constructed.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1809, Napoleon ordered Governor Herman Willem Daendels to improve the defensive systems of Java to protect against a possible British invasion.
[src:bandung/bandung] Daendels ordered the construction of a road stretching approximately 1,000 km (620 mi) from the west to the east coast of Java, passing through Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1810, the road was laid down in Bandung and was named *De Groote Postweg* (or the 'Great Post Road'), the present-day location of Jalan Asia-Afrika.
[src:bandung/bandung] Wiranatakusumah II, the Chief Administrator of the Bandung regency at that time, moved the office from Krapyak, in the south, to a place near a pair of holy city wells (*sumur Bandung*), the present-day site of the city square (*alun-alun*).
[src:bandung/bandung] He built his *dalem* (palace), *masjid agung* (the grand mosque) and *pendopo* (public-official meeting place) in the classical Sundanese orientation, with the pendopo facing Tangkuban Perahu mountain, which was believed to have a mystical ambience.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1856, Bandung also became the capital of the Preanger Regencies Residency, which it would remain until 1925.
[src:bandung/bandung] The first major railroad between Batavia and Bandung was completed in 1880, boosting the light industry in Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Chinese flocked into the city to help run facilities, services and vendors.
[src:bandung/bandung] The area adjacent to the train station is still recognizable as the old Chinatown district.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1906, Bandung was given the status of *gemeente* (municipality), and then twenty years later, *stadsgemeente* (city municipality).
[src:bandung/bandung] From the early 1920s, the Dutch East Indies government made plans to move their capital from Batavia to Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Accordingly, during this decade, the Dutch colonial government commenced construction of military barracks, the building housing the colonial Department of State-Owned Enterprises (*Department van Gouvernmentsbedrijven*, the present-day Gedung Sate) and other government buildings.
[src:bandung/bandung] However, this plan was cut short by World War II, after which the Dutch were not able to re-establish their colony due to the Indonesian Declaration of Independence.
[src:bandung/bandung] The fertile area of the Parahyangan Mountains surrounding Bandung supports productive tea plantations.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the nineteenth century, Franz Junghuhn introduced the cinchona (*kina*) plant.
[src:bandung/bandung] With its cooler elevated landscape, surrounded by major plantations, Bandung became an exclusive European resort area.
[src:bandung/bandung] Wealthy plantation owners visited the city on weekends, attracting ladies and business people from the capital, Batavia.
[src:bandung/bandung] Jalan Braga grew into a promenade street with cafés, restaurants and boutique shops.
[src:bandung/bandung] Two art-deco style hotels, Savoy Homann and Preanger, were built in the vicinity of the Concordia Society, a clubhouse for the wealthy with a large ballroom and a theatre.
[src:bandung/bandung] After Indonesian independence in 1945, Bandung was designated as the capital of West Java province.
[src:bandung/bandung] During the Indonesian National Revolution, some of the most massive battles occurred in and around Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Dutch troops were virtually absent in Java at the end of World War II.
[src:bandung/bandung] To assist the restoration of Dutch sovereignty, British forces established a military presence in several of Java's largest cities, and issued an ultimatum to Indonesian forces in Bandung in an attempt to make them leave the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] In response, on 24 March 1946, much of the southern part of Bandung was deliberately set alight by Indonesian forces as they withdrew.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1955, the first Asian-African Conference, also known as the *Bandung Conference*, was hosted in Bandung by President Sukarno and attended by the heads of states representing twenty-nine independent countries from Asia and Africa.
[src:bandung/bandung] The conference venue was at the Gedung Merdeka, the former Concordia Society building.
[src:bandung/bandung] The conference announced ten points of declaration for the promotion of world peace and opposition against colonialism and is known as the Declaration of Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] This was followed by a wave of nationalism and decolonization movements around the globe which remapped world politics.
[src:bandung/bandung] The conference was also the first international conference of people of colour in history.
[src:bandung/bandung] In his book *The Color Curtain*, Richard Wright claims that there was an epic meaning to the conference for people of colour around the world.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1987, the city boundary was expanded by the 'Greater Bandung' (*Bandung Raya*) plan, with the relocation of higher concentration development zones outside the city in an attempt to dilute population density in the old city.
[src:bandung/bandung] During this development, the city core was often uprooted, with old buildings torn down, lot sizes regrouped and rezoned, changing idyllic residential areas to commercial zones with bustling chain supermarkets, malls, banks and upscale developments.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 2005, an Asian-African Conference was partly held in Bandung, attended by world leaders including Indonesian President Susilo B.
[src:bandung/bandung] Yudhoyono, President of China Hu Jintao, Prime Minister of India Manmohan Singh, President of South Africa Thabo Mbeki and President of Nigeria Obasanjo.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung, the capital of West Java province, is located about 180 kilometres (110 mi) southeast of Jakarta.
[src:bandung/bandung] Its elevation is 768 metres (2,520 ft) above sea level and is surrounded by up to 2,400 metres (7,900 feet) high Late Tertiary and Quaternary volcanic terrain.
[src:bandung/bandung] The 400 km2 (150 sq mi) flat of central Bandung plain is situated in the middle of 2,340.88 square kilometres (903.82 sq mi) wide of the Bandung Basin; the basin comprises Bandung, the Cimahi city, part of Bandung Regency, part of West Bandung Regency, and part of Sumedang Regency.
[src:bandung/bandung] The basin's main river is the Citarum; one of its branches, the Cikapundung, divides Bandung from north to south before it merges with Citarum again in Dayeuhkolot.
[src:bandung/bandung] The Bandung Basin is an essential source of water for potable water, irrigation, and fisheries, with its 6,147 million m3 (217.1 billion cu ft) of groundwater being a significant reservoir for the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] The northern section of Bandung is hillier than other parts of the city, and the unique truncated flat-peak shape of the Tangkuban Perahu volcano (*Tangkuban Perahu* literally means 'upside-down boat') can be seen from the city to the north.
[src:bandung/bandung] Long-term volcanic activity has created fertile andisol soil in the north, suitable for intensive rice, fruit, tea, tobacco, and coffee plantations.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the south and east, alluvial soils deposited by the Cikapundung river predominate.
[src:bandung/bandung] Geological data show that the Bandung Basin is located on an ancient volcano, known as Mount Sunda, erected up to 3,000–4,000 metres (9,800–13,100 feet) during the Pleistocene age.
[src:bandung/bandung] Two large-scale eruptions took place; the first formed the basin, and the second (est.
[src:bandung/bandung] 55,000 BCE) blocked the Citarum river, turning the basin into a lake known as "the Great Prehistoric Lake of Bandung".
[src:bandung/bandung] The lake drained away; for reasons which are the subject of ongoing debate among geologists.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is home to numerous examples of Dutch colonial architecture, most notably the tropical Art Deco, dubbed New Indies Style.
[src:bandung/bandung] Henri Maclaine Pont was among the first Dutch architects to recognize the importance of combining each architectural style with local cultural traditions.
[src:bandung/bandung] He stressed that modern architecture should interact with local history and native elements.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1920, Pont planned and designed buildings for the first technical university in the Dutch East Indies, *Technische Hogeschool te Bandung* (the present-day Bandung Institute of Technology).
[src:bandung/bandung] He was named a Professor of Architecture at the university.
[src:bandung/bandung] A striking local Sundanese roof style is seen adorning the top of the campus' ceremonial hall and is embedded in his artwork.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the same year, another Dutch architect J Gerber designed *Gouverments Bedrijven* (Government Companies) in line with the colonial government's plan to move the capital from Batavia to Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] The building is known as Gedung Sate, named after the distinguished small satay-shaped structure on the roof, and is today used as the head office of the West Java provincial government and House of Representatives.
[src:bandung/bandung] The building is an example of a harmonious mixture between West and East architectural styles, particularly the Italian Renaissance style of arch structures in the wings and pendopo-like structures commonly found in Java in the middle section.
[src:bandung/bandung] Several Dutch architects who shaped the city landmarks the architectural blending of modern and native traditions.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the 1930s, Bandung became known as an architectural laboratory due to the many Dutch architects who experimented with new architectural designs.
[src:bandung/bandung] Albert Aalbers added the streamline moderne style to the Art Deco by designing the DENIS bank (1936) and renovating the Savoy Homann Hotel (1939).
[src:bandung/bandung] Charles Prosper Wolff Schoemaker was one of the architects who enormously added native elements in his artworks, including the Villa Isola (1932), Hotel Preanger (1929), the regional military headquarters (1918), Gedung Merdeka (1921) and ITB Rectorate Building (1925).
[src:bandung/bandung] Though Bandung is known for its many old Dutch architecture buildings, the city is recently going through a high-rise building boom.
[src:bandung/bandung] There are more than 100 high rise buildings in the city, and many more are under construction or planned.
[src:bandung/bandung] The north of the city serves as a water reservoir for Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] However, the area has seen substantial residential development.
[src:bandung/bandung] Several attempts to protect this area have been made, including creating reserves such as the Juanda National Park and Punclut, but development continues.
[src:bandung/bandung] Regular flooding in Bandung's south also presents a real and dangerous ongoing problem.
[src:bandung/bandung] From mid-2005, Bandung faced another environmental disaster when the city's landfill site was re-evaluated after a garbage slide in 2005 which buried a village, Kampung Gajah, beneath it, killing over a hundred people.
[src:bandung/bandung] The accumulation of 8,000 m3/d (3,300 cu ft/ks) of domestic garbage causes severe air pollution by local burning, the spread of disease, and water contamination.
[src:bandung/bandung] The provincial government has failed in its attempts to solve the garbage issue.
[src:bandung/bandung] Nevertheless, it was awarded in 1997 and 2015 as the least polluted city in the country.
[src:bandung/bandung] Further, a regional award in 2017 was also given from ASEAN for the cleanest air among other major cities in ASEAN countries.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is also well known for its tornado hotspot.
[src:bandung/bandung] The first deadly tornado in the area occurred in Rancaekek (during the Dutch Occupation in 1933 where a tornado struck the town, killing 1 and injuring none, the funnel destroyed 17 homes and left 30 homes badly damaged, many trees were either snapped or downed.
[src:bandung/bandung] Another deadly tornado to occur on Bandung was on 18 December 2014, in Gedebage, the tornado struck the area in the afternoon.
[src:bandung/bandung] It left 85 houses either unroofed or destroyed, a large factory building suffered significant damage, a warehouse levelled and a library suffered roof loss, one person died due to crushed by a collapsed wall.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung experiences a tropical monsoon climate (Köppen: *Am*) that closely borders a tropical rainforest climate (*Af*) as the driest month precipitation total is marginally below 60 millimetres (2.4 in).
[src:bandung/bandung] March and August are the wettest and driest months, respectively.
[src:bandung/bandung] The average temperature throughout the year tends to be cooler than most cities in Indonesia due to the influence of altitude.
[src:bandung/bandung] The average temperature throughout the year only has little variation due to its location near the equator.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city area in 1906 was 19.22 square kilometres (7.42 square miles), and by 1987, it had expanded to 167.2965 km2.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city administration is divided into 30 districts (*kecamatan*) and 153 villages (*kelurahan*).
[src:bandung/bandung] For development purposes, the 30 districts are grouped into eight sub-city regions.
[src:bandung/bandung] The sub-city regions of Bandung are Arcamanik, Cibeunying, Kerees, Kordon, Gedebage, Ujungberung, Bojonagara and Tegalega.
[src:bandung/bandung] The mayor (*walikota*) - Bambang Tirtoyuliono from 2023 - leads the city administration.
[src:bandung/bandung] Since 2008, city residents have directly voted for a mayor; previously, mayors were nominated and selected by the city council - the Bandung City Regional House of Representatives (*DPRD Kota Bandung*), which has 50 members.
[src:bandung/bandung] As of 2003, the total number of city administration personnel was 20,163.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung City is divided into 30 districts (*kecamatan*), listed below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 Census and 2020 Census, together with the official estimates as at mid 2022.
[src:bandung/bandung] The table also includes the locations of the district administrative centres, the numbers of administrative villages (totaling 151, all classed as urban *kelurahan*) in each district, and its postal codes.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city's economy is mainly built upon tourism, business, creative industry, high-tech and manufacturing industries, educational institutions, technology, retail services, financial services, pharmaceutical companies, and food production.
[src:bandung/bandung] The once quiet residential district of Dago has become an important business and entertainment centre with chic cafés and restaurants spread out along Jalan Dago.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the early 1990s, Jalan Cihampelas became a popular clothing store location and remains so today.
[src:bandung/bandung] Some important shopping malls of the city which are Trans Studio Mall Bandung, Summarecon Mall Bandung, Bandung Indah Plaza, Cihampelas Walk, Paris Van Java Mall, and 23 Paskal Shopping Center are among the popular shopping centres in Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Creative culture has shaped specific parts of the city's economy.
[src:bandung/bandung] Small businesses, known as "distro", sell non-trademarked products made by local designers.
[src:bandung/bandung] Typical distro products are books, indie label records, magazines, fashion products, and other accessories.
[src:bandung/bandung] Distros are popular with young people and distance themselves from factory outlets in terms of philosophy.
[src:bandung/bandung] They arise from individual designers and young entrepreneurs, while factory outlet products generally come from large-scale garment factories.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city administration has agreed to substantially develop seven industrial and trade areas for Bandung specialty products.
[src:bandung/bandung] These include Binong Jati Knitting Industrial and Trade Center, Cigondewah Textile Trade Center, Cihampelas Jeans Trade Center, Suci (T and Oblong) Shirt Industrial Center, Cibaduyut Shoes Industrial Center, Cibuntu Tofu and Tempeh Industrial Center, Sukamulya Sukajadi Doll Industrial Center.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is a popular weekend destination for residents of Jakarta.
[src:bandung/bandung] The colder climate of the highland plantation area, variety of food, less expensive fashion shops located in factory outlets and distros, golf courses, and the zoo, are some of the attractions of the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is also a popular shopping destination due to the cheap textile and fashion products, especially for Malaysian and Singaporean tourists.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the 1990s, local designers opened denim clothing stores along Jalan Cihampelas, which was transformed into a "jeans street".
[src:bandung/bandung] The city attracts people from other big cities to buy local fashion wares, as they are cheaper than branded items.
[src:bandung/bandung] Beside Jalan Cihampelas, many factory outlets also opened at Jalan Riau, Jalan Braga, Jalan Setiabudi, and Jalan Djuanda (known as Dago).
[src:bandung/bandung] Textile factories on the outskirts of Bandung have opened factory outlets on site selling what is marketed as *sisa export* (rejected or over-produced export quality items).
[src:bandung/bandung] Significant tourist sites near Bandung include the Tangkuban Prahu volcano crater to the north, the Kawah Putih volcano lake, and Patenggang Lake, a lake surrounded by tea plantations about 50 kilometres (31 miles) to the south of the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] To view the Bandung Basin clearly in its mountain surroundings, visitors travel to the Bongkor protected forest area (kawasan hutan lindung), Saung Daweung and Arcamanik; to the slopes of West Manglayang Mountain in an area known as Caringin Tilu, with entry from Padasuka and Cicaheum to the north.
[src:bandung/bandung] The forest is located in 1,500 metres (4,900 feet) above sea level and is covered with pine trees managed by a government corporation Perhutani and can be accessed with 30 minutes drive from downtown.
[src:bandung/bandung] Visitors going to the north of the city also find Taman Hutan Raya Ir.
[src:bandung/bandung] The Cicaheum area also hosts *Bukit Moko*, a tourist spot famous for its views and its steel statue of a giant star called *Puncak Bintang*.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has several museums that should be visited by tourists, such as the Geological Museum of Bandung, the Indonesia Postal Museum, Sri Baduga Museum, and the Asian-African Conference Museum.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city government operates Bandros, a tourist bus, since 2014.
[src:bandung/bandung] Traditionally, Bandung's population is of Sundanese descent.
[src:bandung/bandung] Javanese are the most significant ethnic Indonesian minority and mostly come from the central and the eastern parts of Java.
[src:bandung/bandung] Other minorities include Minang, Minahasan, Chinese, Batak, Malay, Korean, Indian, and Arabs.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung's population are mainly Muslims but small communities of Christians, Hindus and Buddhists also exist in the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 2005, the population of Bandung was 2.29 million people with a density of 13,690/km2 (35,457/sq mi).
[src:bandung/bandung] The May 2010 census enumerated 2.395 million people and that of May 2020 enumerated 2.444 million.
[src:bandung/bandung] Based on data from Statistics Indonesia, the population of Bandung in mid 2023 was 2,506,603 (comprising 1,259,236 males and 1,247,367 females), making Bandung the third-most populous city in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is a significant cultural hub in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] Most people in the surrounding province of West Java are ethnically Sundanese, with Sundanese often spoken as a first language, and the standard and informal language for communication in streets, school, work, and markets.
[src:bandung/bandung] As in the rest of the country, standard Indonesian serves as the *lingua franca* and primary language of government, business, media, and formal education.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is one of the cities in Indonesia with a rich musical history, known for traditional instruments such as the Angklung, Suling, and Kacapi, which are commonly used in Tembang Sunda.
[src:bandung/bandung] Since the Dutch colonial era, Bandung has been the center of music in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has notable UNESCO with creative cities with specially music band is majority founded over there.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bands such as Kahitna, The Changcuters, SM*SH, Yovie & Nuno, Noah, and Project Pop were founded and established in Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is the home of Persib Bandung, a professional football club currently competing in the highest tier of Indonesian football, the *Liga 1*.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung is also home of Prawira Bandung (ex Garuda Bandung), a professional basketball club currently competes in the Indonesian Basketball League, with its home games in the *GOR Citra Arena*.
[src:bandung/bandung] The roads leading up to Lembang and Dago are popular routes for mountain cycling on weekends, as Jalan Ir.
[src:bandung/bandung] Djuanda and Jalan Buah Batu is zoned as car-free on Sunday mornings.
[src:bandung/bandung] Other popular sports in Bandung include badminton and golf, with several golf courses surrounding the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has several local daily newspapers, including *Pikiran Rakyat*, *Galamedia*, and *Tribun Jabar*.
[src:bandung/bandung] Several local television stations operate in Bandung, including TVRI Jawa Barat (a public regional station serving West Java, which headquartered in the city), Bandung TV, MQTV and PJTV.
[src:bandung/bandung] Many radio stations, such as Ardan FM, KLCBS, MQFM and OZ Radio, also broadcast from Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] The city of Bandung was featured in the 9th and 10th leg of the American reality series *The Amazing Race 23*.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung can be accessed by highways from Jakarta.
[src:bandung/bandung] An intercity toll highway called Cipularang Toll Road, connecting Jakarta, Karawang, Purwakarta, Padalarang and Bandung, was completed in May 2005, and is the fastest way to reach Bandung from the capital by road.
[src:bandung/bandung] Driving time is about 1.5 hours on average.
[src:bandung/bandung] There are three other options: the Puncak route (Jakarta-Cianjur/Sukabumi-Bandung), Purwakarta route (Jakarta-Cikampek-Purwakarta-Cikalong Wetan-Padalarang-Cimahi-Bandung) and the Subang route (Jakarta-Cikampek-Subang-Lembang-Bandung).
[src:bandung/bandung] From cities further east (Cirebon, Tasikmalaya and Central Java province), Bandung can be accessed through the main provincial road.
[src:bandung/bandung] Indonesian National Route 3 links Bandung with the rest of Java towards Cilegon and Ketapang (Banyuwangi).
[src:bandung/bandung] The Pasupati Bridge was built to relieve traffic congestion in the city for east–west transport.
[src:bandung/bandung] The 2.8-kilometre (1.7 mi) cable-stayed bridge lies through the Cikapundung Valley.
[src:bandung/bandung] It is 30 to 60 metres (98 to 197 feet) wide and, after extensive delays, it was finally completed in June 2005, following financial investment from Kuwait.
[src:bandung/bandung] The bridge is part of Bandung's comprehensive inner-city highways plan.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has two intercity bus terminals: Leuwipanjang, serving buses from the west, and Cicaheum, serving buses from the east.
[src:bandung/bandung] Both are at full capacity and are to be replaced by a new terminal at Gedebage on 15 hectares (37 acres) land, after which the old terminals will function as inner-city terminals.
[src:bandung/bandung] The new terminal will be located next to the Gedebage railway station near Gedebage container dry port.
[src:bandung/bandung] Taxis and Carpooling are widely available.
[src:bandung/bandung] The primary means of public transportation is by *angkot* minibuses (from *angkutan*, "transportation" and *kota*, "city"); *angkot* are privately operated and serve multiple routes throughout the city, and although cheap, they are considered basic and uncomfortable.
[src:bandung/bandung] To find exact angkot routes, passengers may look for information available through the drivers or at terminals.
[src:bandung/bandung] Due to the current extent of railway lines in Bandung, only two named regional railway services, *Lokal Bandung Raya* and *Lokal Garut Cibatuan*, are serving the city, serving a single line.
[src:bandung/bandung] It catered for the suburban areas east and west of the city such as Cimahi, Padalarang, Rancaekek, Cicalengka, as well as some other neighbouring towns such as Garut and Purwakarta.
[src:bandung/bandung] KAI Commuter took over the operations of both services from its mother company KAI in 2022, anticipating planned electrification of the route by Ministry of Transport.
[src:bandung/bandung] Boseh is a dock-based bicycle-sharing system provided by the Transport Service (*Dinas Perhubungan*) of Bandung.
[src:bandung/bandung] Public buses in Bandung and its surrounding urban area are operated by various operators, with a total 16 bus lines currently operating.
[src:bandung/bandung] *DAMRI* buses used to dominate as the main bus operator serving the city and its surrounding metropolitan area, first operating in the 1970s, with at some point operating more than 10 routes.
[src:bandung/bandung] However, it collapsed in October 2021, leaving 5 routes still operating.
[src:bandung/bandung] Following the example of TransJakarta, the city government introduced its own BRT system called Trans Metro Bandung on 24 September 2009.
[src:bandung/bandung] By 2022, it served 5 trunk corridors and 1 feeder routes.
[src:bandung/bandung] Both DAMRI and Trans Metro Bandung buses uses higher deck buses similar to TransJakarta, but could be stopped anywhere along its route and do not run separately from traffic.
[src:bandung/bandung] Provincial government of West Java also operates a bus route called as Safe and Healthy Bus Rapid Transit (shortened Buratas), serving only a single line.
[src:bandung/bandung] As part of nationwide bus services modernization program called as Teman Bus, a more disciplined system branded as Trans Metro Pasundan was introduced by central government's Ministry of Transportation in December 2021.
[src:bandung/bandung] Two operators, Big Bird (part of Blue Bird Group) and DAMRI operated 5 routes inherited from former DAMRI routes under a contract with Ministry of Transport.
[src:bandung/bandung] Introduction of new bus routes in Bandung often faced resistance from *angkots* and extortion attempts by so-called local patrons due to perception that their revenues being stolen, leading to blockades and verbal threats against bus drivers.
[src:bandung/bandung] Due to fragmentation of brands and operators, passengers must pay again when transiting to other bus lines or to other modes such as trains.
[src:bandung/bandung] Only Trans Metro Pasundan has integrated tariff, enabling users not to pay again when transferring to other routes within the system.
[src:bandung/bandung] A more comprehensive plan to revitalize the bus system will be implemented in 2024, extending from the Trans Metro Pasundan project.
[src:bandung/bandung] It would integrate all operators within a single system called Trans Bagja, with proper Bus Rapid Transit features such as dedicated lanes, frequent bus availability and bus stops.
[src:bandung/bandung] The planned system intended to use electric powered buses, both imported and locally produced.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung city government also operated a fleet of city tour buses called as Bandung Tour on Bus (shortened Bandros).
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has two large railway stations, Bandung and Kiaracondong Stations.
[src:bandung/bandung] Other smaller stations are Cimindi, Andir, Ciroyom, Cikudapateuh, and Gedebage Stations.
[src:bandung/bandung] Railway lines connect Bandung to Cianjur, Jakarta, Purwakarta, Bekasi, Karawang, and Cikampek to the west, and Surabaya, Malang, Yogyakarta, and Solo to the east.
[src:bandung/bandung] The Whoosh high-speed rail line currently provides train service from nearby Padalarang and Tegalluar to Jakarta's Halim station.
[src:bandung/bandung] Due to constraints, stations serving Bandung are neither within Bandung city centre nor the limits of Bandung city.
[src:bandung/bandung] Instead, a feeder service will ply between Padalarang HSR station and the main Bandung station, using existing tracks.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung's main airport, Husein Sastranegara Airport (BDO).
[src:bandung/bandung] The airport is located near the Dirgantara aerospace complex and Dirgantara Fairground.
[src:bandung/bandung] The Kertajati International Airport in Majalengka Regency was built to replace the Husein Sastranegara Internasional Airport.
[src:bandung/bandung] Redevelopment of the existing Husein Sastranegara Internasional Airport (BDO) was completed in 2016.
[src:bandung/bandung] The new and larger second airport for the Greater Bandung Area; Kertajati International Airport (KJT) opened in June 2018, just in time for the 2018 Asian Games.
[src:bandung/bandung] On 11 July 2023, Indonesian President Joko Widodo announced that Husein Sastranegara Internasional Airport will be retired and all commercial flights will be moved to Kertajati starting October 2023 when it is fully operational.
[src:bandung/bandung] Bandung has nearly 50 higher educational institutions and is among the most popular destinations for education in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] There are hundreds of public and private schools in the city and several state-funded and administered Junior High Schools (SMP Negeri), State High Schools (SMA Negeri) and State Vocational School (SMK).
[src:bandung/bandung] At least sixteen universities—three of which are state-owned—and 45 professional schools are scattered across the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] Education from social sciences and technology to tourism education can be found at one of these universities.
[src:bandung/bandung] Established in 1920, ITB is Indonesia's oldest and most prestigious technical university.
[src:bandung/bandung] Universitas Pendidikan Indonesia (formerly IKIP Bandung, established in 1954) is one of the first institutions of higher education established after Indonesian independence and is currently a leading education university in the country.
[src:bandung/bandung] Universitas Padjadjaran (established in 1956) is considered to be one of the best universities in the country in the fields of medicine, law, communication, and economics.
[src:bandung/bandung] International schools are also available in the city.
[src:bandung/bandung] They include the Bandung Alliance Intercultural School, Bandung Independent School, Bandung Japanese School (バンドン日本人学校), Bina Bangsa School Bandung, Bina Persada School, and Stamford School.
[src:bandung/bandung] In the north of Bandung, Bosscha Observatory is the only observatory in Indonesia.
[src:bandung/bandung] Construction of the observatory began in 1923 and was completed in 1928.
[src:bandung/bandung] In 1922, the first international publication from Bosscha Observatory was published, and in 1959, the observatory was absorbed as a part of the Department of Astronomy at the Bandung Institute of Technology.
[src:bandung/bandung] Several countries have set up their consulates in Bandung, including France, Netherlands, Poland, Latvia, Hungary, Austria, etc.
